@NODE DESCR "Libraries description"

    @{b}Libraries description:@{ub}

  Actually, the new set support 2 libraries :

    Window  (Blitz 2 Library Number = 27)
    Screen  (Blitz 2 Library Number = 26)


  Now, a little table to see the size difference between use of new  set
  commands  and  old  Blitz  2 commands. All theses executables has been
  produced with debugger OFF. The result is given  in  bytes,  it's  the
  final executable size.


                        | Old Blitz 2 Commands | New libary set commands |
                        |----------------------+-------------------------|
  Windows only commands |    14 000 bytes      |            600 bytes    |
  Screen  only commands |     7 700 bytes      |            500 bytes    |


  Command descriptions:

    @{"  Window  " LINK WINDOW}
    @{"  Screen  " LINK SCREEN}

@ENDNODE




@NODE SCREEN "The screen commands"

    @{b}The screen commands descriptions:@{ub}

 
  For all the commands which return an ScreenID, you must  use  an  long
  typed  variable  (.l) to store this value. It's an standard pointer to
  an Intuition  Screen  so  you  can  use  it  directely  (for  advanced
  programmers).  If  ScreenID  = 0 then the command has failed. Easy for
  testing.


  There is 11 screen specifics commands:

  ScreenID = NFindScreen - Return The FrontMost Screen.

  ScreenID = NWbToScreen - Try to find the Wb Screen

  ScreenID = NScreen(TagList) - Opened a new screen

  It  open  a  new  screen  with  the  taglist parameter. TagList aren't
  difficult tp use and are totally  system  friendly,  so  old  Screen()
  syntax is no more supported.

  NSMouseX - Return the mouse x position

  NSMouseY - Return the mouse y position

  NScreenWidth - Return the width of the used screen

  NScreenHeight - Return the height of the used screen

  NShowScreen - Put the used screen to front of display

  NHideScreen - Put the used screen in back of the display

  UseScreen(ScreenID) - Change the used screen

  CloseScreen(ScreenID) - Close the specified screen

@ENDNODE


@NODE WINDOW "The Window commands"

    @{b}Window commands description:@{ub}

  For all the commands which return an WindowID, you must  use  an  long
  typed  variable  (.l) to store this value. It's an standard pointer to
  an Intuition  Window  so  you  can  use  it  directely  (for  advanced
  programmers).  If  WindowID  = 0 then the command has failed. Easy for
  testing.

  There is 20 windows specifics commands:

  WindowID = NWindow(TagList) - Open a new window

  It open a new  window  with  the  taglist  parameter.  TagList  aren't
  difficult  to  use  and  are  totally system friendly, so old Window()
  syntax is no more supported.

  NWMouseX - Return the mouse x position

  NWMouseY - Return the mouse y position

  NWindowWidth - Return the width of the used window

  NWindowHeight - Return the height of the used window

  NWindowX - Return the x position of the used window

  NWindowY - Return the y position of the used window

  NRastPort - Return the used window RastPort pointer

  NWColour(FrontColour, BackColour) - Set the default colour

  This comand affect both graphics functions and  texts  output  on  the
  window.


  NWLocate(X,Y) - Set the default cursor text position

  NWPrintFast(String$) - Print the string on the window

  This command is faster  than  original  one  because  it  use  another
  function instead. But it's not as powerful (You can't mix numeric with
  text)


  NWindowTextStyle(Style) - Set the style for used window text output

  The  legals  Style  value are:
    * 0 = Nothing
    * 1 = Underline
    * 2 = Bold
    * 4 = Italic
  You can mix it if needed (Bold+Italic will be 2+4 = 6)


  NWMove(X,Y) - Move the used window to the given coordinates -

  Note: If you must do several NWMove one after other, you MUST check if
  the window is moved or not. Or you can put a delay  (Delay_  5)  after
  this command to avoid any bugs.


  NWSize(Width, Height) - Resize the window to the given dimensions -

  Note: If you must do several NWSize one after other, you MUST check if
  the  window  is  sized or not. Or you can put a delay (Delay_ 5) after
  this command to avoid any bugs.


  NWindowFont(FontID) - Set the window font to the given font.

  It MUST be an legal IntuiFont Pointer. New Font library coming soon.


  NWPlot(X,Y) - Draw a plot on the window

  It's a TOTALLY system friendly function. It use  the  WritePixel()  OS
  Function to achieve that.


  NWBox(x1, x2, y1, y2) - Draw a solid box on the window

  It's a TOTALLY system friendly function.  It  use  the  RectFill()  OS
  function  so  you  MUST  give  the parameter in the right order (clock
  order)


  NActivate(WindowID) - Activate the specified window

  UseWindow(WindowID) - Change the used window

  CloseWindow(WindowID) - Close the specified window

@ENDNODE


